{{Infobox person | name = Beto Carrero | image = Beto Carrero 01.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = João Batista Sergio Murad | birth_date = {{Birth date|1937|9|9}} | birth_place = [[São José do Rio Preto]], [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo]], [[Brazil]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2008|2|1|1937|9|9}} | death_place = [[São Paulo]], [[Brazil]] | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = {{hlist|Theme park owner|businessman|entertainer}} | years_active = }}
[[Image:Beto-Carrero.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Entrance to the Beto Carrero World]]'''Beto Carrero''' (born '''João Batista Sergio Murad'''; September 9, 1937 &ndash; February 1, 2008) was a [[Brazil]]ian [[theme park]] owner and [[entertainer]]. He was the creator of the [[Beto Carrero World]] Park, which bears his name, in the municipality of [[Penha, Santa Catarina|Penha]], on the northern coast of the Brazilian state of [[Santa Catarina (state)|Santa Catarina]].
==Biography== Carrero was born into a poor family of Lebanese immigrants in [[São José do Rio Preto]] and worked as a [[Música sertaneja|Sertanejo]] musician, radio announcer and ad salesman before starting an advertising agency and, later, a theme park.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
He owned what has been called the largest theme park in [[Latin America]], [[Beto Carrero World]] in [[Penha, Santa Catarina|Penha]], which he owned from its opening in 1991 until his death. He also appeared in several acting roles under his stage persona, a [[vaqueiro]].
On January 30, 2008 he was admitted to [[Hospital Sírio-Libanês]], in [[São Paulo]], with a cardiac problem and died two days later. The official cause of death was [[endocarditis]]. He is survived by three sons.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jj4yj37U9DWYfLMh8iNpt2MokknAD8UI4TD80 |title=Obituaries in the News |publisher=Associated Press |date=2008-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218135144/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jj4yj37U9DWYfLMh8iNpt2MokknAD8UI4TD80 |archivedate=2008-02-18 |df= }}</ref><ref>(Portuguese){{cite news |url=http://exclusivo.terra.com.br/interna/0,,OI2305080-EI1118,00.html |title=Empresário Beto Carrero morre em São Paulo (Entrepreneur Beto Carrero dies in São Paulo) |publisher=Terra (Brazil) |date=2008-02-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204102917/http://exclusivo.terra.com.br/interna/0%2C%2COI2305080-EI1118%2C00.html |archivedate=2008-02-04 |df= }}</ref>
In June 2008, [[journalist]] ''Alex Solnik'' released a [[biography]] of Beto Carrero. It was titled ''Domador de Sonhos - A Vida Mágica de Beto Carrero'' (which means, in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], ''Tamer of Dreams - The Magical Life of Beto Carrero'').<ref>(Portuguese){{cite news|url=http://odia.terra.com.br/cultura/htm/biografia_do_empresario_beto_carrero_traz_historias_dos_bastidores_da_tv_178673.asp|title=Biography of Beto Carrero|publisher=O Dia (Brazil)|date=2008-06-17|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617215746/http://odia.terra.com.br/cultura/htm/biografia_do_empresario_beto_carrero_traz_historias_dos_bastidores_da_tv_178673.asp|archivedate=2008-06-17|df=}}</ref>
== Comics == In 1985, the ''As Aventuras de Beto Carrero'' [[comic book]] was published by [[Cluq Editorial]], written by Gedeone Malagola and with art by Eugenio Colonnese. Although based on Bandeiras and Sertanejo periods, started in at the end of the 17th century. In the comics Beto did not use [[firearm]]s, but instead his [[whip]], to fight crime.<ref>↑ Fransérgio Rodrigues (2008). Velho Oeste Brasileiro, Revista Mundo dos Super-Heróis #9. Editora Europa. pp. 11. </ref>
In November 2006, JB World Entertainment SA, Carrero's illustration and animation studio, launched the comic book ''The Adventures of Betinho Carrero''. The title is about a young fan of Beto Carrero who dresses like him.<ref>{{cite book|author=Fransérgio Rodrigues|title=Velho Oeste Brasileiro, Revista Mundo dos Super-Heróis #9|publisher=Editora Europa|year=2008|pages=11|id=}}</ref>
