[[File:Sir Daniel Dixon by Henrietta Rae.jpg|thumb|right|Portrait of Dixon by [[Henrietta Rae]]]]
[[Image:Sir Daniel Dixon.jpg|thumb|right|Monument to Sir Daniel Dixon, grounds of [[Belfast City Hall]], [[Northern Ireland]]]]
'''Sir Daniel Dixon, 1st Baronet''', [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (I)]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (28 March 1844 – 10 March 1907) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] businessman and politician.

==Early life==
Dixon was born on 28 March 1844 the son of Thomas and Sarah Dixon of [[Larne]], [[County Antrim]], his father was a merchant and shipowner.<ref name="obit" /> He was educated at the [[Royal Belfast Academical Institution]].<ref name="obit" /> He joined his father's timber business, Thomas Dixon and Sons, becoming a partner in 1864.

==Political career==
He served as [[Mayor of Belfast]] in 1892 and as [[Lord Mayor of Belfast]] in 1893 and from 1901 to 1903 and from 1905 to 1906. He was also a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Belfast North (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast North]] as an [[Ulster Unionist Party|Ulster Unionist]] from 1905 to 1907.

Dixon was appointed to the [[Privy Council of Ireland]] in the [[1902 Coronation Honours]] list published on 26 June 1902,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation Honours |day_of_week=Thursday |date=26 June 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36804| }}</ref> and was sworn in by the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]], [[George Cadogan, 5th Earl Cadogan|Earl Cadogan]], at [[Dublin Castle]] on 11 August 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ireland |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=12 August 1902 |page_number=9 |issue=36844| }}</ref> In October 1903 he was created a '''Baronet''', of Ballymenock in the County of Antrim.

==Businessman==
Dixon was head of one of the largest shipowning companies in Ireland.<ref name="obit">"Sir. Daniel Dixon." Times [London, England] 11 Mar. 1907: 6. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 10 Apr. 2014.</ref>

==Family life==
Dixon married, firstly, Lizzie, daughter of James Agnew, in 1867. After his first wife's death in 1868 he married, secondly, Annie, daughter of James Shaw, in 1870. He died on 10 March 1907 in Belfast, aged 62, and was succeeded in the baronetcy by his eldest son [[Sir Thomas Dixon, 2nd Baronet|Thomas]]. Lady Dixon died in 1918.

